    {
        "docId": "7475cbc5-ba4f-4441-b74f-4ad2bc147d25",
        "type": "lessons learned",
        "title": "SIMOPS in aux while running WL",
        "description": "Good experience on building 7\" tubing in aux while running wireline.\n\nTwo learning points noted down after first WL runs:\n1. \nLower sheave tie down point: As of now, the only certified point to anchor the lower sheave is the padeye on the deck at the V door. There are 3 problems using this padeye. One, we need the 15T tugger to support the weight of the sheave wheel. Since the sheave is so far outside of the derrick, the tugger tries to pull the sheave wheel into the floor. We managed this well. Secondly, the position of the padeye can cause the shackles to interfere with the handrail at the V door. We found a position to minimize contact, but ideally if we continue to use that padeye, a small section of the lower rail can be removed. Thirdly, history shows us that the most likely place for a wireline cable to break is at the top sheave. When this happens, all of the cable between the top and bottom sheave will fall to the floor. By having the lower sheave wheel so far away from the top, it increases the exposure area should something happen. This is the exact area where the SIMOPS are taking place. The ideal place to install the lower sheave is closer to the well. The samson post outside of the driller’s cabin would be ideal, but as of now it’s not certified.\n\n2.\nMisconception between «POOH» and «Logging» - In the risk assessment performed, it was decided that SIMOPS should not continue during overpulls or while POOH, and only while RIH and logging. The misconception is that logging is usually performed while POOH, albeit at a slower speed. When we POOH with MSCT sidewall cores, we POOH at a slow speed, similar to and sometimes slower than logging speed. During the operation, SIMOPS were stopped for 2 hours while POOH with sidewall cores because we used the term POOH. The limitation for SIMOPS should be cable speed and not whether or not it’s called POOH. I suggest a speed limit of 8000 ft/hr as a safe cable speed for SIMOPS to proceed.",
